[b]Casino Club[/b]

Carrom with chips on the table. Coins carry banked chip value; pockets become wagers on a craps-style casino spin. Win the board by bankrupting the opposition.

[b]Setup[/b]
• Casual carrom rules apply (no Queen-cover requirement, no penalty coin returns).
• Each player starts with a stack of chips in the bays along their edge.
• Every coin on the board carries a [b]base value[/b] — uniform across white, black, and queen.

[b]Coin Hoards[/b]
• Hitting a coin can spawn a loose chip token next to it. Coins and the striker collect any token they touch.
• The striker carries its hoard until its first contact with a coin — at which point the entire hoard transfers onto that coin. The coin's chip face updates to show its new total.
• Each coin has an [b]optimum hoard[/b] of 5× the current base value. Anything above that is [b]overload[/b] — visible as a taller chip stack on the coin's face.
• Overload is allowed and can grow as large as you can build it (the god-coin path — see Tactics).

[b]Hoard Redistribution[/b]
• [b]Coin → coin contact[/b] is the only way an overloaded coin sheds its excess. When an overloaded coin contacts another coin, its over-cap chips fly off to the contacted coin, and the overloaded coin returns to its optimum.
• [b]Striker → coin contact[/b] does NOT shed overload. A hard strike on an overloaded coin lets you sink it for its full uncapped wager.
• Overloaded coins do not "decay" on their own — only collisions normalise them.

[b]The Chip Economy[/b]
• Pocket your own coin (or the Queen): your opponent pays the coin's value (base + hoard) to the [b]house[/b] as a wager on the casino game. The chips visibly leave their stack and enter the house pile while the spin plays out.
• Pocket an opponent's coin alongside your own: that opp coin ALSO triggers its own wager + spin — drained from the opp's stack, settled by its own casino spin. [b]One spin per coin[/b] pocketed (own or opp), provided at least one own coin was pocketed in the shot.
• Order doesn't matter — opp pockets that fire before any own pocket are held; if a later own pocket arrives, each held opp pocket gets its own wager + spin; if the turn ends with no own pocket fired, the held opp pockets discard with no chip movement.
• Pocket an opponent's coin on a pure foul (no own pocket): no chip movement, no spin. The opp coin is removed from play. Your turn ends; nothing leaves the opponent's stack. The foul is its own consequence.
• Pocket the striker / strike off the board / hit no own coin: foul — your turn ends. No wagers fire from this shot.

[b]Fouls Don't Erase Chips[/b]
• Tokens left on the board stay on the board.
• Chips stuck to coins (coin hoards) stay on those coins.
• Chips carried on the striker (striker hoard) stay on the striker.
• A fouled shot moves zero chips between stacks.

[b]The Casino Game[/b]
• Each scoring pocket fires a two-ring craps spin at the centre of the board.
• The outer ring pays out on positions [b]5[/b] and [b]6[/b]; the inner ring pays out only on position [b]6[/b]. Awards sum across rings.
• [b]Win:[/b] the house pays you the wager [b]and[/b] takes the winnings (wager × the award multiplier) from your opponent to pass to you. Your opponent pays everything; the house breaks even; you get it all. Total transferred to you = wager × (1 + award).
• [b]Loss:[/b] the wager (already with the house from pocket time) stays with the [b]house[/b] — your opponent paid; you got nothing; the house keeps it.

[b]Mystery Boxes[/b]
• The house spawns mystery boxes onto the board to recycle captured chips back into play.
• Hit a mystery box to reveal its chip value and add it to the nearest coin's hoard (or the striker's, if the striker hit it).
• Mystery-box payouts can push a coin into overload (no cap on this path).

[b]Board Respawn[/b]
• When the last coin is cleared, the board respawns with all coins back in the centre.
• Each respawn [b]increments[/b] the chip base value by a fixed amount (default +100, uncapped). Later boards stake bigger swings — and bigger foul opportunities — without the runaway exponential blow-out of the old doubling rule.
• The hoard optimum is always 5× the current base, so the cap escalates with the stakes.

[b]Winning[/b]
• The match ends the instant any team's combined chip stack reaches zero.
• That team is bankrupt — the opposing team wins the board.

[b]Player Configurations[/b]
• [b]1v1[/b], [b]2v2[/b], [b]1v1v1[/b], or [b]1v1v1v1[/b] — all carrom configurations are supported. Multi-player games may end early as the first player to bust drops out.

────────────────────────────────────────

[b]Tactics[/b]

[b]Build a god-coin[/b]
• Load a single coin past the 5× optimum to set up a massive single-pocket wager.
• The path: hoard chips on the striker (token sweeps with no coin contact), then on a later shot send the striker through the star to absorb its hoard, then strike the chosen coin so the striker dumps its entire hoard onto it. The coin can also keep collecting from mystery boxes or in-flight tokens.
• [b]Critical:[/b] once the coin is overloaded, it must reach a pocket [i]without touching another coin[/i] — any coin↔coin contact will shed the over-cap chips onto the receiver, fragmenting the god-value. Striker contact is safe (striker doesn't normalise).

[b]Sand shot — capture the opponent's god-coin[/b]
• When the opponent loads a coin but can't immediately pocket it, drive a shot that pockets [b]your own coin AND the opp's loaded coin together[/b].
• Because every pocket — own or opp — fires its own wager drained from the opp team, you collect [b]own_base + opp_base + opp_hoard[/b] from your opponent. The god-coin value flows to you, and the attacker who built it pays the bill.
• This is the single hardest counter to land but the most lucrative — the harder the opp banked into one coin, the bigger your sand shot pays.

[b]Reflective conversion — steal a loaded coin's hoard[/b]
• Send one of your [b]own coins[/b] into an overloaded opp coin.
• The coin↔coin contact triggers redistribution: the opp coin's overload sheds onto your own coin.
• You now have a loaded own coin to pocket on a later shot — and the opp's stash has been turned against them without you committing a striker line.

[b]Sacrificial removal — eliminate the threat[/b]
• Pocket the loaded opp coin on a pure foul (no own coin pocketed in the shot).
• You lose the turn, but the opp coin is permanently removed from play and the hoard goes with it. No chip movement either way.
• Useful when the opp coin's geometry doesn't allow a sand shot or reflective conversion, and leaving it would invite a god-coin pocket on the opp's next turn.

[b]Lateral fragmentation[/b]
• Knock an overloaded opp coin into [b]another opp coin[/b].
• Redistribution still fires — the excess fragments, but it stays on the opp's side of the table.
• Weakest defensive option, but cheap (no own coin spent, no turn lost). Useful as a holding move when better counters aren't available.

[b]Hard pocket — committed conversion[/b]
• When YOU have a loaded own coin lined up for a pocket, hit hard and commit. The full coin value (base + hoard) drains from the opp the moment it pockets, and the striker's bounce can be used to position for the next shot.
• Hard-pocketing a loaded own coin is the cleanest way to cash a built-up hoard.

────────────────────────────────────────

[b]Defending an overloaded opp coin — quick guide[/b]
• Can you pocket it with one of your own in the same shot? → [b]Sand shot[/b] (best).
• Can you reach it from one of your own coins on the table? → [b]Reflective conversion[/b].
• Is it isolated and dangerous? → [b]Sacrificial removal[/b].
• Is none of the above on offer? → [b]Lateral fragment[/b], or accept the risk.
